The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Friday, February 20, 2004  The City Diary
																																																																																		Admit cards for the Higher Secondary examination will feature scanned copies of the candidates photographs, instead of the passport-size originals, from this year, said authorities of the West Bengal Council of Higher Secondary Education on Thursday. The decision has been taken to prevent impersonation during examination.																																																		Surojit Chatterjee, 45, died on Wednesday night on Vidyasagar Setu in the Hastings police station area when his motorcycle skidded and crashed on to the pavement. The resident of Brajamani Diba Road was rushed to SSKM Hospital where he succumbed to head injuries. Police said Chatterjee was speeding down the bridge without wearing a helmet.																																																		The high court on Thursday rejected the bail petition of Tarun Bhattacharya, a promoter in Jagaddal, North 24-Parganas, who after converting to Christianity married Jolly of Kanchrapara, a woman of the same faith. He had not disclosed that he had married earlier. Jolly lodged a complaint with Bijpur police when she came to know that Tarun was married and had a son.																																																		A division bench of Calcutta High Court on Thursday refused to pass an interim order on the high court appeal challenging the order of Justice Pratap K. Roy of the same court imposing an interim stay on the transfer order of a family court judge to West Midnapore. 																																																								he family court judge, Chitra Biswas, who claimed she was handicapped, had challenged the decision of the administrative committee of Calcutta High Court, which had turned down her petition to block the transfer order. The high court authorities filed an appeal against the trial court order, but the division bench observed that the matter should be first heard by the trial judge.																																																		Finance minister Asim Dasgupta on Thursday promised to lift the existing ban on appointment of non-teaching employees in state-aided secondary schools in and outside Calcutta, sources said.																																																		Dipali Das, who ran a drug-peddling racket, was arrested in her house in the Kidderpore area on Wednesday evening. Heroin worth more than Rs 1 lakh was recovered from her.																																																		A Calcutta High Court advocate filed a petition on Thursday challenging the validity of setting up a circuit bench of the high court at Jalpaiguri. The petitioner contended that the authorities concerned did not bother to take the permission of Parliament and asked for an order restraining the authorities from taking any further step. The matter will come up for hearing in a couple of days.TO Ramakrishna Mission Seva Pratishthan employees co-operative stores amp; canteen for distributing sweets and fruits to 500 patients of Seva Pratishthan
